The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                               SPORTS BRIEFS
                
	PCB not in favour of   2-tier plan  
	 Karachi: The Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) has made it clear that it would not support the proposal to have a two-tier international calendar that would be discussed by the ICC committees next week in Johannesburg.   
	There are strong rumours that India, Australia, England and South Africa are supporting a two-tier system of competitions in the new Future Tours Program that runs from 2012 to 2020. In the proposed system, which would have a relegation and promotion system, Pakistan has been put in the lower tier alongside New Zealand, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka and the West Indies.      
	BCB president    Dhaka: A.H.M. Mostafa Kamal has been appointed president of the Bangladesh Cricket Board (BCB), replacing Sina Ibn Jamali, a Board statement said Wednesday. Kamal is a member of parliament and a senior figure in the ruling Awami League of Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina, who won election in December 2008.  
	Atwal for Open  
	 New Delhi: The Indian Open golf tournament, scheduled from October 8 to 11, got a massive boost with former champion Arjun Atwal confirming his participation in the $1.25 million Asian Tour event next month.    
	Atlanta: Fourteen-time PGA Tour champion Kenny Perry, who donates five per cent of his winnings to a university scholarship fund, won the Payne Stewart Award on Tuesday. The honour is bestowed annually on a player sharing Stewart rsquo;s respect for the traditions of the game and his commitment to uphold golf rsquo;s heritage of charitable support.  
	All Al Nahyan rsquo;s  
	London: Manchester City are now wholly owned by Arab billionaire Sheikh Mansour bin Zayed Al Nahyan after the Premier League club said Wednesday he had bought the remaining 10 per cent of the shares.  
	Sol choice 
    London: Sol Campbell rsquo;s shock move to League Two (fourth division) Notts County lasted just one match after the England defender was allowed to tear up his five-year contract on Wednesday, the club said.
        
	 Tashkent: Top seed Yaroslava Shvedova of Kazakhstan beat Ekaterina Ivanova of Russia 7-5, 6-2 Wednesday to reach the quarter finals of the Tashkent Open.         
	 New Delhi: The Delhi High Court Wednesday restrained boxer Vijender Singh from signing any deal with event management firm Percept Ltd.     
	The courts direction came over a petition filed by celebrity management company Infinity Optimal Solutions (IOS), which claimed it had an exclusive agreement with the pugilist till September 2015.                                                                                                                                                                        
